<h2>Two tiers — build the cheap one first</h2>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Verdict floor — a lightweight task-specific classifier (feasible now).</strong> ≲10 MB
    quantized, runs in-browser on any device, distilled from the dev-gate verdicts. This is the
    fixed-cost floor that makes the verdict-gated features flat-rate-safe.</li>
  <li><strong>Richer tier — a small on-device VLM (heavier, later).</strong> For tagging / element
    detection / structure; ≲2B device ceiling; structure recovery stays hard (Design2Code SOTA ≈76 —
    see <a href="/research/design-ref-vision/">design-ref-vision</a>).</li>
</ol>

<h2>Three framing principles (author steers) — targets, not rejections</h2>
<p>
  AI capability moves fast, so this decision is deliberately framed as a <em>moving target</em>, not a
  one-shot model pick:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Benchmark to reach, don't reject.</strong> What's out of reach today may be feasible in
    months. Each tier gets a <em>graduation benchmark</em> (a metric + threshold it must hit to move
    on-device); until a tier clears it, the hosted-API / bring-your-own-key provider is the
    <strong>always-on bridge</strong> that ships the feature now. A feature is never "rejected" — it's
    "below threshold, on the API bridge."</li>
  <li><strong>Re-assess on a cadence.</strong> A recurring re-benchmark of the small-model frontier
    against the graduation targets (the <a href="/backlog/192-longitudinal-research-freshness-system/">#192</a>
    longitudinal / dated-revision model, same shape as the gap-sweep re-run) flips a tier on-device the
    moment it clears.</li>
  <li><strong>Codify the training as a model-agnostic, re-applicable artifact.</strong> The durable
    assets are the <em>labeled corpus</em> (#489) + the <em>distillation recipe</em> + the
    <em>benchmark suite</em> — not any one trained model. Switching base model means
    <strong>re-running the recipe, never re-labelling from scratch</strong>. This is
    <a href="/research/">minimize-lock-in</a> applied to the model itself: the model is the swappable
    part, the training pipeline is the kept part.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Architecture fit — a provider swap, not new plumbing</h2>
<p>
  The on-device model is an <strong>implementation behind the existing swappable vision-provider seam</strong>
  (<code>scripts/design-refs/vision.mjs</code> → <code>registerVisionProvider</code>), the same seam
  <a href="/backlog/475-design-ref-vision-gated-capture-qc-candidate-surface-quality/">#475</a> ruled and
  #480/#485 built. Adding an on-device tier is registering another provider; the WE standard never imports
  it, so the <strong>no-leakage invariant holds</strong> (only verdicts/outputs flow on). Per the #091
  managed-offering layering, the served capability is a Plateau/impl concern, not a WE-standard artifact.
</p>

<h2>What this feeds</h2>
<p>
  Five prepared forks in <a href="/backlog/488-on-device-ui-screenshot-vision-model-as-a-plateau-capability/">#488</a>:
  the two capability tiers + their graduation benchmarks, the build method (distil-from-corpus), the
  runtime home (in-browser WebGPU), the pricing tiering (on-device floor + API bridge/upgrade, never
  per-usage-only-forever), and the re-assessment cadence + codified-training artifact.
</p>
